choices.text: the election of Ellen Johnson Sirleaf of the Unity Party to the Presidency on September 10, 2005. She is the first elected female president of an African country in history. A refugee from conflict when she fled the country in 1980, she came back to an uncertain future. She was elected President of the Republic of Liberia on October 11, 2005 at the end of poll counting with a staggering 58.4 % of first votes cast. This was a landslide victory in a nation deeply wounded by civil war for the better part of the past 23 years. A great number of kind, refreshing struggles helped to achieve this milestone. Failed attempts of other credible candidates created a growing sympathy for her to mobilize over 400 groupings of women's organizations, other than leading a powerful crusade against her opponents in public. Person held unofficial contests, forging women's groups to convince others to give their vote. Lenora Young-Bunch, aPeace Corps Volunteer from 70 years ago had worked diligently to organize women to make CHOICE for themselves in strong numbers. The contribution of a great female donor, Gamre, bleach Banda and other women all played roles in demonstrating the integrity of the person. Obstinacy and persistence on the part of other groups to gather the desired numbers were characteristic of her success.
